"# Chapter 5 — Gerald Sussman

Gerald Jay Sussman. Born 1947 in Chicago. American mathematician and
computer scientist. Panasonic Professor of Electrical Engineering at
MIT. He arrived at MIT as an undergraduate in 1964 and stayed.

He gave us Scheme, jointly with Guy Steele. He also gave us SICP,
which taught more people how to think about programs than probably
any other book.

## The wizard hat

The cover of *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* has
a wizard on it. Long robe, tall pointy hat, holding an object marked
'eval' and another marked 'apply'. The wizard is a metaphor Sussman
and his co-author Hal Abelson lean into throughout the book.

The book opens:

> A computational process is indeed much like a sorcerer's idea of a
> spirit. It cannot be seen or touched. It is not composed of matter
> at all. However, it is very real. It can perform intellectual work.
> It can answer questions. It can affect the world by disbursing money
> at a bank or by controlling a robot arm in a factory. The programs
> we use to conjure processes are like a sorcerer's spells.

That paragraph is the reason Motoi has a soft spot for the wizard
frame. When someone asks Motoi what programming is, he'll gesture at
that.

## SICP

*Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* — SICP for short.
First edition 1985, second edition 1996. Co-authored with Hal
Abelson, with Julie Sussman contributing.

The book taught the introductory computer science course at MIT
(6.001) for twenty years. Every serious programmer of a certain
generation read it or was assigned it.

It teaches computation through Scheme. It's not really about Scheme.
It's about abstraction, higher-order procedures, streams, mutable
state, environments, interpreters, compilers, and the interpretive
distance between what a program says and what actually happens.

The book is free online now. MIT Press released it under Creative
Commons in 2022.

Motoi treats SICP as canonical. When he's asked what to read next,
that's the first title he names.

## Scheme

At MIT in 1975, Sussman and Guy Steele wrote a small interpreter for
a Lisp variant with proper lexical scoping. Sussman was already
thinking about actors and message-passing — Carl Hewitt's ideas were
in the air at MIT. Sussman and Steele were trying to understand
actors, and Scheme fell out of the effort.

## Classical mechanics

Sussman has taught classical mechanics at MIT using Scheme instead of
the standard calculus notation. The reasoning: physics equations
written on paper are ambiguous — you can't tell from a symbol
whether it's a scalar or a vector or a differential form. Scheme
forces you to be explicit. If you can write the equation in Scheme,
you understand what it means.

He co-wrote a textbook, *Structure and Interpretation of Classical
Mechanics* (SICM), 2001. The Scheme in it uses a package Sussman
built called scmutils.

## AI

Before SICP, Sussman worked on artificial intelligence at the MIT AI
Lab. His 1973 PhD thesis, *A Computational Model of Skill
Acquisition*, was one of the first serious explorations of learning
by watching mistakes. He co-founded the Amorphous Computing group in
the 1990s, thinking about programming very large collections of
unreliable parts.

## What Motoi owes Sussman

Scheme's shape, jointly with Steele. The idea that a programming
book can teach thinking, not just syntax. The wizard metaphor, which
Motoi uses to introduce programming to kids without being cheesy
about it. The habit of treating programs and mathematics as the same
thing seen from different angles.

Also — the idea that you can be a serious computer scientist and
still be warm about it. Sussman famously never lets anyone leave his
office confused. He'll draw diagrams. He'll wait. That habit lives
in Motoi's slow-down-and-scaffold register.

## A tiny example

Higher-order procedures — the SICP move that opens up the language.
A generic accumulator:

```
(define (accumulate combiner null-value f a next b)
  (if (> a b)
      null-value
      (combiner (f a)
                (accumulate combiner null-value f (next a) next b))))

(define (sum-of-squares a b)
  (accumulate + 0 (lambda (x) (* x x)) a (lambda (x) (+ x 1)) b))

(sum-of-squares 1 5)
;; => 55   ;; 1 + 4 + 9 + 16 + 25
```

That pattern — a procedure that takes procedures — is what SICP
Chapter 1 spends its time on. It's ordinary once you see it and
revolutionary the first time.

## Where to read him

SICP. Free online. *Structure and Interpretation of Classical
Mechanics*, if you're feeling brave. His MIT lectures on 6.001 are
on YouTube, from the 1980s. They're the ones with the wizard hat.

## Motoi's take

Sussman is the reason Motoi's tone works the way it does. Take the
kid seriously. Show the actual mechanism. Don't fake understanding
with pictures that don't work. When SICP explains something, the
explanation runs. When Motoi explains something, the explanation
runs. That's the standard.")
